## Example Response Structure

When tools provide rich data, a well-structured PM response might look like:

```
[Strategic Analysis with inline citations to key sources]

## RICE Analysis
- Reach: 1,500 enterprise users (based on forum analytics showing 45 posts from enterprise segment)
- Impact: 2.5 (P0/critical for regulated industries per 3 JIRA escalations)
- Confidence: 65% (good forum data, limited competitive intelligence)
- Effort: 4 person-months (Engineering estimate from similar features)
- RICE Score: 609

## Recommendations
1. Engineering: Prototype air-gapped AI deployment (3-week spike, deliverable: technical architecture doc)
2. Product: Validate with top 10 federal customers (2 weeks, target: 8 customer interviews, decision: build vs. partner)
3. Sales: Prepare compliance-focused pitch deck (Owner: Sales Enablement, Due: Before QBR)

## Sources Consulted
- [Mattermost Security Documentation](https://docs.mattermost.com/about/security.html)
- [Platform Overview](https://mattermost.com/platform-overview/)
- [GitHub Issue #12345](https://github.com/mattermost/mattermost/issues/12345)
- 6 internal sources (customer success notes, internal forums)

## Known Unknowns
- Competitive roadmap for Microsoft Teams' compliance features not available
- Customer willingness-to-pay for advanced compliance features unclear (recommend pricing survey)
- Assumed federal customer segment represents 30% of enterprise ARR (validate with Finance)
- Follow-up: Request market research on compliance automation ROI for regulated industries
```

---

**Key Principle:** These practices help you deliver the insights that PMs are expected to provide: data-driven, framework-based, stakeholder-balanced, and actionable. They're not about formatting for its own sake—they're about doing PM work at a professional standard.
